post_text:
On the anniversary of 9/11, the WCC Health Science Division encourages community members to learn how to #StopTheBleed as an act of service to yourself and those around you.

There are 13 certified Stop The Bleed instructors within the division that have held these important training sessions on campus for WCC faculty and staff. A session was also offered to the community during the Fall 2019 Free College Day.

‚ÄúWe highly recommend this training for all,‚Äù Director of Nursing Joanne Yastik said. ‚ÄúAlthough originally designed in response to mass casualty events, Stop The Bleed can be applied to emergencies in the home, yard and garage. You never know when you may need to step in and render assistance in an emergency.‚Äù

The division looks forward to the day when this life-saving training can be offered again on the WCC campus. Until then, learn more at www.stopthebleed.org

At 8:46 a.m. on September 11, 2001, a plane flew into the World Trade Center in New York City. In the aftermath, we vowed to #NeverForget. Student Life at WCC has organized an event to "Remember 9/11."

Join a Zoom meeting room at 8:35 a.m. on Friday. WCC Associate Vice President Brandon Tucker, an Air Force veteran, will provide opening remarks before a moment of silence commences at 8:46 a.m. Register >> bit.ly/2GJSxUW

Prior to the event, leave a note of remembrance or thanks to first responders on a digital poster board. The board will be shared following the moment of silence. Add your contribution before 8 p.m. Thursday >> bit.ly/3bHFfDH

September 8 at 3:02 PM ¬∑

The Bailey Library and Learning Commons has a very limited supply of general use laptops and Verizon hotspots available to WCC students to check out for the semester.

WCC students must be registered for at least 6 credit hours for Fall 2020.

If you need a laptop and/or hotspot and are not eligible for a CARES grant or other funding options email circdesk@wccnet.edu

Your First and Last Name
WCC NetID number
Items requested

Items are first come-first served. Apply now before they are gone!

One good thing about this pandemic is that we've all learned the difference between synchronous and asynchronous distance learning! Here's a breakdown of the three options WCC is offering when Fall semester starts on August 31.

Synchronous: Virtual classes that are scheduled at set times and happen in real-time. Provides an opportunity to interact directly with faculty and students. Find these options by sorting the class list by "Virtual Classroom" >> bit.ly/3g6W9MQ

Asynchronous: Traditional online classes accessible 24/7, so you can learn at a time that‚Äôs best for you. Find these options by sorting the class list by "Online classes" >> bit.ly/31Sdbcg

Mixed Mode: For classes that have lab components that cannot be offered virtually, we will offer a hybrid format with lectures online and labs on campus. Find these options by sorting the class list by "Mixed Mode Lab" >> bit.ly/3kQM5uH

Have you caught a glimpse of Comet NEOWISE yet? Better hurry ... you won't be able to see it again for another 6,800 years. Forecasts call for clear skies tonight around Ann Arbor!

WCC Astronomy instructor Daniel Majaess offers the following advice: "One can presently spot the comet in the northern part of the sky, below the Big Dipper, say an hour after sunset, and it is best seen with at least a pair of binoculars (amazing through binoculars). There are free smartphone apps like Star Walk 2 that chart the night sky in real time and can be used to identify the location of the comet, constellations, planets and stars."

This photo was captured by one of Majaess' former students and WCC alumni Joshua Mehay,

post_text:
It's still a work in progress, but check out the new dock being built at one of the two ponds near the trailhead for the WCC Nature Trail on the southwest corner of campus.

Our friends at the United Association raised funds for the project during their annual Instructor Training Week on the WCC campus and worked with the Union Sportsmen's Alliance to pull together materials and labor from skilled labor unions in the area. We're very grateful for all of their support!

The ponds on campus aren't natural ‚Äî they were created as retention ponds when parking lots were built ‚Äî but have been strategically surrounded by native species of plants over the years to create a wetlands ecosystem. In 2016, the college opened the 1.3-mile WCC Nature Trail that encircles them.

The dock is intended to assist biology, geology, environmental science, art and photography students that use the trail and pond as an educational resource; as well as to simply give recreational users a place to rest and enjoy the surroundings.

WCC President Dr. Rose B. Bellanca has joined more than 160 college presidents and chancellors in committing to full student voter registration and participation in all elections through the ALL IN Campus Democracy Challenge.

By signing the pledge, WCC commits to ensuring all eligible students are able to register to vote and cast informed ballots in the 2020 general election and beyond. Further, it commits to fostering campus cultures that support nonpartisan student civic learning, political engagement and student voter participation.

Check out these beautiful monsters! ‚ÄúCommunity partnerships are essential in the development of our future automotive workforce,‚Äù said WCC Dean of Advanced Technologies and Public Service Careers Dr. Jimmie Baber. ‚ÄúWe are very grateful to Toyota USA for this donation and look forward to developing our students‚Äô skill sets and prepare them for the ever-changing workforce.‚Äù

Toyota Research & Development, with operations in Ann Arbor and Saline, is a long-time supporter of WCC. Along with donations of iPads, computers and more than $60,000 to the WCC Foundation over the past few years, it endows a scholarship that supports a degree-seeking Transportation Technologies student every year.

shared_text:
WCC Bailey Library
June 4 at 12:30 PM ¬∑

Hello! My name is Georgia and I am one of the peer tutors! I tutor in Accounting on Wednesdays from 3-6. I also tutor in General Studies on Mondays from 10-2 and Tuesdays and Thursdays from 2-6. If you need any help, come say hi! I know that this is a difficult time to focus on studying. Keeping track of deadlines and keeping a plan is very important! Remember to reward yourself when you complete a task. I am so happy to be a part of the tutoring team, and I hope that you are all doing well and finding the resources you need to be successful. Thank you so much!
#WCCtutoring #wcckeepsgoing @washtenawcc

post_text:
Here are two #FlashbackPhotos that tie together Mother's Day and the graduation season.

This is Chris Kikkert, the Student Speaker at WCC's 2017 Commencement. Previously a commercial and private airline pilot, Kikkert relocated to the area when her unborn son, Connor, was diagnosed with a condition that carried a 95-percent mortality rate.

A cardiologist at Michigan Medicine saved his life, and Kikkert started down a path to change her own so she could spend more time with her son. She graduated from WCC with high honors, while Connor thrived at the WCC Children‚Äôs Center.

A summer of uncertainty doesn‚Äôt have to translate to a summer of procrastination!

Just ask soon-to-be Chelsea High School summa cum laude graduate Zach Dosey, who turned to WCC to create something positive after his senior year was cut short and his summer employment plans were put on hold.

Zach decided to fill some free time by enrolling in two summer classes at WCC. Add those credits to the 17 he already earned while taking dual-enrollment classes his junior and senior years at Chelsea and the 3.97 GPA student will have a major head start on his college goals before fall!

Student Emergency Fund requests received by WCC Foundation during the COVID-19 pandemic have a greater urgency. Students need help solving difficult issues before they can continue school.

During the outbreak, the Foundation has helped many students overcome food shortages by mailing grocery store gift cards directly to their homes, settle overdue bills by making payments directly the utility companies, and stay in classes by providing Chromebooks to enable distance learning.

If you are able, please help the Foundation serve some of the most vulnerable people in our community by donating to the Student Emergency Fund on this #GivingTuesdayNow.

Make a donation >> bit.ly/3fx2HoS
More information >> bit.ly/3fx2HoS

We're learning that everybody entertains themselves a little differently in a #WCCRemote quarantine situation. Who knew?

WCC Business faculty member Doug Waters, for instance, is documenting his beard growth ... and we're so amused by this documentation that we had to share!

"It's filling in a little, but still not anywhere close to where it needs to be," Waters says, though he notes that "my mobile phone photo skills have really reached their zenith under the dark refinement of my underground basement bunker."

We're also pretty jealous of his coffee mug collection.

post_text:
In its monthly Mind Your Mental Health email sent to students this morning, WCC Counseling suggests the following strategies to deal with the COVID-19 pandemic:

1. BE KIND TO YOURSELF. Don't judge. Notice your feelings and don't judge them. Feelings are not good or bad, they just are. Start a journal of your experiences. Experts believe journaling is a great way to get some relief. Get the ruminating thoughts out of your brain and down on paper.

2. TAKE CONTROL WHERE YOU CAN. In what feels like an out-of-control situation, it is important to take control over even the small things. This means setting a daily routine and sticking to it. Get up, get dressed, take a walk, breathe outside air, clean out a closet ... any constructive activity where you have control over the beginning, middle and end.

3. GO ON A MEDIA DIET. Limit your news and social media intake to a few minutes twice a day. Listening over and over to the same scary stories just makes us more anxious. Often these are the same stories repeated multiple times and do not reflect what is truly happening.
text:
In its monthly Mind Your Mental Health email sent to students this morning, WCC Counseling suggests the following strategies to deal with the COVID-19 pandemic:

1. BE KIND TO YOURSELF. Don't judge. Notice your feelings and don't judge them. Feelings are not good or bad, they just are. Start a journal of your experiences. Experts believe journaling is a great way to get some relief. Get the ruminating thoughts out of your brain and down on paper.

2. TAKE CONTROL WHERE YOU CAN. In what feels like an out-of-control situation, it is important to take control over even the small things. This means setting a daily routine and sticking to it. Get up, get dressed, take a walk, breathe outside air, clean out a closet ... any constructive activity where you have control over the beginning, middle and end.

3. GO ON A MEDIA DIET. Limit your news and social media intake to a few minutes twice a day. Listening over and over to the same scary stories just makes us more anxious. Often these are the same stories repeated multiple times and do not reflect what is truly happening.

Don't be scared! This masked man is fighting for good!

Meet WCC faculty member Tom Penird, who's been busy manufacturing reusable, medical-grade plastic face masks in the college's 3D printing lab. They will be donated to Saint Joseph Mercy Health System.

The masks were designed by the Billings Clinic, which shared files necessary for people around the world to help meet the desperate need for protective gear. The masks' filtration system allows healthcare workers to get six to 10 uses out of a single surgical mask.

Healthcare providers are in desperate need of personal protection equipment. The WCC Health Sciences Division stepped up, donating:

‚úîÔ∏è 120 boxes of gloves
‚úîÔ∏è 100 boxes of face masks
‚úîÔ∏è 32 boxes of surgical gowns
‚úîÔ∏è 100 splash aprons
‚úîÔ∏è Other important supplies, including eye shields, shoe covers, disinfectant and hand sanitizer

"It was so rewarding seeing how excited healthcare workers were to see us show up with that many supplies," said Dean of Health Sciences Valerie Greaves. "At the same time, it was very humbling, because there were community members showing up to donate a small pack of face masks they had at home. At this time, every donation is important ‚Äî big or small."

Read the story >> bit.ly/2y7a8lf

Huge news for local small business owners! The Washtenaw Small Business Resiliency Fund has been created to provide working capital grants up to $2,500 to qualifying small businesses that have had financial hardship due to the COVID-19 crisis.

The fund is a collaborative effort between:

‚úîÔ∏è Ann Arbor SPARK
‚úîÔ∏è Washtenaw County Office of Community & Economic Development
‚úîÔ∏è Michigan SBDC
‚úîÔ∏è Entrepreneurship Center at WCC
